initial_story: in recent years, classical convolutional neural networks (cnns) have beenapplied for image recognition successfully. quantum convolutional neuralnetworks (qcnns) are proposed as a novel generalization to cnns by usingquantum mechanisms. the quantum mechanisms lead to an efficient trainingprocess in qcnns by reducing the size of input from $n$ to $log_2n$. this paperimplements and compares both cnns and qcnns by testing losses and predictionaccuracy on three commonly used datasets. the datasets include the mnisthand-written digits, fashion mnist and cat/dog face images. additionally, dataaugmentation (da), a technique commonly used in cnns to improve the performanceof classification by generating similar images based on original inputs, isalso implemented in qcnns. surprisingly, the results showed that dataaugmentation didn't improve qcnns performance. the reasons and logic behindthis result are discussed, hoping to expand our understanding of quantummachine learning theory.
stories: In recent years, classical convolutional neural networks (CNNS) have yielded significant success in image recognition. Building on CNNS, quantum convolutional neural networks (QCNNS) introduce innovative quantum mechanisms to enhance efficiency during the training process. These mechanisms drastically shrink the input size from n to log2n, streamlining training in QCNNS. This paper compares both CNNS and QCNNS by benchmarking losses and prediction accuracy on popular datasets, specifically the MNIST handwritten digits, Fashion MNIST, and Cat/Dog face images. Moreover, data augmentation (DA), commonly employed in CNNS to boost classification rates, is applied in QCNNS as well. Counterintuitively, the results reveal that data augmentation did not yield a performance boost for QCNNS. The motivations and theoretical reasoning for this outcome are discussed to further our understanding of quantum machine learning theories.

Compared with CNNS, this paper evaluates both by assessing losses and prediction accuracy on familiar datasets like MNIST, Fashion MNIST, and Cat/Dog images. Similarly, data augmentation, widely used in CNNS to enhance classification, is applied to QCNNS, yet surprising results show no performance gain was attained. Insights into the theories behind these findings are presented to advance quantum machine learning understanding.
